# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
overview:<p>The Corvis sees very little use on the modern battlefield, with only Clan Hell's Horses still manufacturing this obsolete design at the Niles Industriplex Alpha facility. Introduced in the mid-twenty-ninth century, the Corvis drew on the Star League Mercury BattleMech's semi-modular weapon port concept, representing an early step toward what would eventually become OmniMech technology. Though frequently dismissed as underpowered for its forty-ton weight class, the design's modular weapons and jump capability have made it a practical support platform for the combined-arms operations that define Hell's Horses military doctrine.</p>

capabilities:<p>Built on a Model MH-24 endo steel chassis with seven tons of Compound H17 ferro-fibrous armor, the Corvis uses a 160-rated fusion engine that limits its top speed to just 65 km/h, making it one of the slowest medium BattleMechs in any Clan arsenal. Four Model KT jump jet boosters compensate for this lack of speed, providing a 120-meter jump range that makes the design valuable in restricting terrain such as urban environments and dense forests.</p><p>The Corvis's semi-modular weapon ports allow field technicians to swap primary armament systems without the full pod reconfiguration capability of a true OmniMech. While this modularity is limited compared to later designs, it provides more flexibility than a standard BattleMech and allows garrison commanders to tailor loadouts to expected threats. The primary limitation remains the chassis's modest tonnage budget, which constrains both armor protection and weapons payload relative to more modern Clan medium designs.</p>

deployment:<p>The Corvis 2 is a Jihad-era refit introduced in 3075 that replaces the UAC/10 with a Class 20 Hyper-Assault Gauss Rifle and upgrades the medium pulse lasers to heavy medium lasers. A targeting computer enhances accuracy for both weapon systems. The chassis, armor, engine, and jump capability remain identical to the standard Corvis while delivering substantially more firepower at the cost of increased ammunition dependency.</p>

history:<p>The Corvis was developed by Clan Hell's Horses in the mid-twenty-ninth century at Niles Industriplex Alpha. Drawing on the Star League Mercury BattleMech's semi-modular weapon port concept, the Corvis represented an early experiment in modular 'Mech design that would have far-reaching consequences for Clan warfare.</p><p>Clan technicians expanded on the Corvis's modular design philosophy to create the Omni-Corvis prototype OmniMech in 2921. This experimental design debuted during the fateful Battle of Tokasha, where Clan Ghost Bear seized control of the planet and its manufacturing facilities. In retaliation for Khan Kilbourne Jorgensson's death, Ghost Bear released the Omni-Corvis blueprints on the Chatterweb, scattering the design across Clan space. Only Clan Snow Raven pursued the plans further, ultimately refining them into the Stormcrow -- one of the most successful OmniMechs in Clan history -- by 2930.</p><p>Despite the Stormcrow's overwhelming success, Clan Hell's Horses continued manufacturing the Corvis at Niles. Often deployed as support for conventional troops such as combat vehicles and infantry, the original design found a lasting niche in combined-arms operations that fit perfectly with the Horses' military doctrine. By the thirty-first century, no other Clan maintained production of this largely obsolete but historically significant design.</p>

